## Generating the 3D structure of TWIST1

Let's download the TWIST1 protein `.fasta` file. More details about TWIST1 in humans can be found here: https://www.uniprot.org/uniprotkb/Q15672/entry


```python
!pip install requests

import requests

def download_file(url, directory, filename=None):
    local_filename = filename if filename else url.split('/')[-1]
    with requests.get(url, stream=True) as r:
        r.raise_for_status()
        with open(os.path.join(directory, local_filename), 'wb') as f:
            for chunk in r.iter_content(chunk_size=8192):
                f.write(chunk)
    return local_filename

url = 'https://rest.uniprot.org/uniprotkb/Q15672.fasta' # TWIST1 in humans

twist1_fasta_filepath = download_file(url, PROJECT_DIR)
```

Now that the `.fasta` file has been downloaded, we can fold the protein using [ColabFold](https://www.nature.com/articles/s41592-022-01488-1).


```python
from plex import CoreTools, plex_create

sequences = [twist1_fasta_filepath]
dir_path = f"{PROJECT_DIR}"

initial_io_cid = plex_create(CoreTools.COLABFOLD_MINI.value, dir_path)
```


```python
from plex import plex_run

completed_io_cid, completed_io_filepath = plex_run(initial_io_cid, outputDir=PROJECT_DIR)
```

# In silico docking with Equibind

So far, we've run Colabfold and generated TWIST1 `.pdb` files. Now we can run in-silico docking. We'll use the small molecule ADQ, which was discovered to be an inhibitor of TWIST1 in this [paper](https://www.nature.com/articles/s41598-021-95933-4).


```python
ADQ_download_url = 'https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/rest/pug/compound/CID/44219712/record/SDF?record_type=2d&response_type=display'

def remove_filename_from_path(file_path):
    return os.path.dirname(file_path)

# removes io.json from path
completed_io_filepath = remove_filename_from_path(completed_io_filepath)

# we specify to download the .sdf file at the same location as the
# outputs of the colabfold run so we can run docking
download_file(ADQ_download_url, completed_io_filepath, "ADQ.sdf")
```

Now we can dock ADQ to TWIST1 using Equibind.


```python
initial_binding_io_json_cid = plex_create(CoreTools.EQUIBIND.value, completed_io_filepath)
completed_binding_io_json_cid, completed_binding_io_filepath = plex_run(initial_binding_io_json_cid, outputDir=PROJECT_DIR)
```

We've just completed a basic in-silico pipeline, starting from the amino acid sequence of TWIST1, to its folded 3D structure, to a docking simulation between TWIST1 and ADQ. If you'd like to investigate the results, you can explore the CID of the IO JSON, which points to all input and output data from running Equibind. We recommend downloading the outputs for the highest ranked folded protein and ADQ, then visualizing the binding using a tool like [MolStar Viewer](https://molstar.org/viewer/).
